      transliteration: 'yoga-sthaḥ kuru karmāṇi saṅgaṁ tyaktvā dhanañjaya\nsiddhy-asiddhyoḥ samo bhūtvā samatvaṁ yoga ucyate',
      translation: 'Perform your duty equipoised, O Arjuna, abandoning all attachment to success or failure. Such equanimity is called yoga.',
      words: [
        { word: 'yoga-sthaḥ', meaning: 'established in yoga / standing in union' },
        { word: 'kuru karmāṇi', meaning: 'perform your duties / do your actions' },
        { word: 'saṅgam tyaktvā', meaning: 'having abandoned attachment' },
        { word: 'dhanañjaya', meaning: 'O winner of wealth (Arjuna)' },
        { word: 'siddhi-asiddhyoḥ', meaning: 'in success and failure / in achievement and non-achievement' },
        { word: 'samaḥ bhūtvā', meaning: 'having become equal / being even-minded' },
        { word: 'samatvam', meaning: 'equanimity / evenness of mind' },
        { word: 'yogaḥ ucyate', meaning: 'is called yoga / is said to be yoga' }
      ],
      commentary: `Yoga is defined here — and the definition is not what most people expect. It is not a posture. It is not a breathing technique. Yoga is samatvam — evenness of mind across success and failure. To act from your established self rather than from the craving for one outcome or the dread of another.\n\nYour peace does not depend on what happens. Your effort does not change based on whether it will work. You act because it is right to act, and you remain the same whether the result goes your way or does not. This is the hardest teaching in the Gita to actually practice. But it is also the only kind of peace that cannot be taken away — because it does not rest on external circumstances.\n\nNotice what Krishna adds: act from yoga-sthaḥ — "established in yoga." Not reaching for yoga. Not hoping for it. Established. This suggests that the first step is actually finding that inner ground — through practice, through stillness, through whatever it takes to know your own centre. Once you know it, you can act from it. Before you know it, equanimity is just a word.`,
      youtubeShort: { title: 'Your Peace Should Not Depend on Results | Gita 2.48', url: 'https://www.youtube.com/shorts/_8paeAb7Z0U' }
