      devanagari: 'दूरेण ह्यवरं कर्म बुद्धियोगाद्धनञ्जय ।\nबुद्धौ शरणमन्विच्छ कृपणाः फलहेतवः ॥',
      transliteration: 'dūreṇa hy avaraṁ karma buddhi-yogād dhanañjaya\nbuddhau śaraṇam anviccha kṛpaṇāḥ phala-hetavaḥ',
      translation: 'Action motivated by results is far inferior to action performed with the yoga of wisdom, O winner of wealth. Take refuge in this wisdom-yoga. Pitiful are those who make results their motive.',
      words: [
        { word: 'dūreṇa hi avaram karma', meaning: 'action for results is far inferior / is much lower' },
        { word: 'buddhi-yogāt', meaning: 'than the yoga of wisdom / than wisdom-guided action' },
        { word: 'dhanañjaya', meaning: 'O winner of wealth (Arjuna)' },
        { word: 'buddhau śaraṇam anviccha', meaning: 'seek refuge in this wisdom / take shelter in the intelligence' },
        { word: 'kṛpaṇāḥ phala-hetavaḥ', meaning: 'pitiful are those who make results their motive' }
      ],
      commentary: `The word kṛpaṇāḥ — pitiful, miserable — is striking. It is the same root as the word used in verse 7 when Arjuna described his own state (kārpaṇya-doṣa). The person who makes results their motive for action is, in Krishna's view, in a state of poverty — not material poverty, but existential poverty. They have placed the meaning of their effort in a domain they cannot control.\n\nDūreṇa hy avaram — "far inferior." Not slightly worse, not a minor difference — far inferior. Action performed with the eye fixed on results is a fundamentally lower quality of engagement than action performed from the yoga of wisdom. The difference is not in the action itself but in the inner orientation of the actor.\n\nBuddhi-yoga — the yoga of wisdom-guided action — is the alternative. Act from your deepest understanding. Act from your values, your dharma, your clearest sense of what is right. And release what happens as a result into the hands of something larger than your preference. This is the upgrade Krishna is offering: not better outcomes, but a better way of acting from which better outcomes naturally, though not always, follow.`
