      transliteration: 'śrī-bhagavān uvāca\nprajahāti yadā kāmān sarvān pārtha mano-gatān\nātmany evātmanā tuṣṭaḥ sthita-prajñas tadocyate',
      translation: 'The Blessed Lord said: O Partha, when one gives up all the cravings of the mind — and remains content within the Self by the Self alone — such a person is called one of steady wisdom.',
      words: [
        { word: 'śrī-bhagavān uvāca', meaning: 'the Blessed Lord said' },
        { word: 'prajahāti yadā kāmān sarvān', meaning: 'when one has given up all desires' },
        { word: 'pārtha', meaning: 'O son of Pritha (Arjuna)' },
        { word: 'mano-gatān', meaning: 'that dwell in the mind / mental desires' },
        { word: 'ātmani eva ātmanā tuṣṭaḥ', meaning: 'content within the Self by the Self alone' },
        { word: 'sthita-prajñaḥ tadā ucyate', meaning: 'is then called one of steady wisdom' }
      ],
      commentary: `The portrait of the sthitaprajña begins here, and the first quality identified is the most foundational: ātmani evātmanā tuṣṭaḥ — content in the Self by the Self alone. Not content because circumstances are good. Not content because desires have been satisfied. Content because the Self has found its source within itself and rests there.\n\nThis is the distinction between conditional and unconditional peace. Conditional peace — "I am at peace because things are going well" — is always one event away from collapse. Unconditional peace — "I am at peace because I am rooted in something that does not depend on circumstances" — is what the Gita is pointing toward. The Self is its own sufficiency.\n\nThe phrase prajahāti — gives up, releases — is important. It is not that desires never arise. It is that when they arise, they are released rather than clung to. This is not suppression. It is the natural byproduct of having found something more satisfying than any desire could point to. When you are truly full, you do not grasp at food. When the Self knows its own fullness, it does not grasp at the objects desire promises.`
