      transliteration: 'duḥkheṣv anudvigna-manāḥ sukheṣu vigata-spṛhaḥ\nvīta-rāga-bhaya-krodhaḥ sthita-dhīr munir ucyate',
      translation: 'One whose mind is not disturbed even in the threefold miseries, who is not elated when there is happiness, and who is free from attachment, fear and anger — such a person is called a sage of steady mind.',
      words: [
        { word: 'duḥkheṣu', meaning: 'in miseries / in sorrows' },
        { word: 'anudvigna-manāḥ', meaning: 'whose mind is undisturbed / unagitated' },
        { word: 'sukheṣu vigata-spṛhaḥ', meaning: 'free from desire in happiness / without craving in pleasure' },
        { word: 'vīta-rāga', meaning: 'free from attachment / without passion' },
        { word: 'bhaya', meaning: 'fear' },
        { word: 'krodhaḥ', meaning: 'anger' },
        { word: 'sthita-dhīḥ', meaning: 'of steady wisdom / of stable intelligence' },
        { word: 'muniḥ ucyate', meaning: 'is called a sage / is said to be a contemplative one' }
      ],
      commentary: `This verse begins the portrait of the sthitaprajña — the person who has truly found their centre. And the description is striking for what it does not say. It does not say they never feel pain or never know joy. It says their mind is not disturbed by pain and not inflated by joy. These are two different things.\n\nThe experience arrives. But it does not take over. The person who has truly figured life out is not the one who has eliminated difficulty. It is the one who has found something inside themselves that does not move when difficulty arrives. Rāga, bhaya, krodha — attachment, fear, anger. These three are listed because they are the three primary ways the unrooted mind reacts to experience: it clings to what it wants, fears what might come, and rages at what does not go its way.\n\nThe rooted mind simply is. It receives experience with the same quality of presence it brings to everything else. Pain does not destroy it. Success does not inflate it. It remains recognisably itself. This is the Gita's portrait of the fully realised human being — not spectacular, not otherworldly, but simply stable in a way that almost nothing in ordinary life prepares us for.`,
