      commentary: `The ocean metaphor is perfect. Rivers pour into it constantly — and yet the ocean remains the ocean. It does not become agitated by the volume of incoming water. It does not swell with pride when the monsoon comes, or contract in fear when a drought follows. It simply holds. Its vastness means no single stream can define it.\n\nKrishna is saying that the person who has found their inner stillness is like this. Desires arise — they always will. Desire is not a problem in itself; it is part of being alive. But they enter and the person remains undisturbed. This is not suppression. The rivers still flow. The difference is that the ocean is vast enough that no single river can alter its fundamental nature.\n\nThis is the teaching the Gita offers as an alternative to both indulgence and repression: a third way, which is the way of the ocean. Not blocking desires. Not chasing them. Being so fully established in yourself that they pass through without possessing you. When you are grounded in your own depth, desire moves. It does not rule.`,
