      commentary: `The chapter closes with the destination named. Brāhmī sthitiḥ — the Brahmic state — is the condition of one who has become established in Brahman, the Absolute, the ground of all existence. Not a momentary glimpse, not a temporary experience, but a state — a stable establishment in what is real.\n\nTwo promises are made. First: having attained this, one is never again deluded. Not "rarely deluded" or "less frequently deluded." Never. The confusion about what is real and what is not — which is the root of all suffering in the Gita's understanding — is dissolved by direct knowledge of the Brahmic state. You cannot be confused about something you directly know.\n\nSecond: even at the moment of death, one who is established in this attains brahma-nirvāṇa — liberation, the peace of the Absolute. This is the teaching at the end of Chapter 8 as well (8.5, 8.7): the quality of awareness you carry into the final moment determines where you go. The person who has genuinely found the Brahmic state carries it into death, and what they carry is what they enter.\n\nChapter 2 has moved from Arjuna's collapse to the portrait of the sthitaprajña to the promise of the Brahmic state. The distance from the beginning to the end of this chapter is the entire journey of the Gita in miniature.`
